utweigh the wider costs and no reliable basis upon which to introduce </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tolls. Since all up-front funding for the works will need to come from Government and public partners, and revenue from tolling could not be derived until 2020 at the earliest, such an analysis would not need to dela</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">y the start of the improvements;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:4.14pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The imp</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">osition of tolls on the A14 would be arbitrary and outwith any coherent policy on road-user charging. With the exception of the M6 toll (to which there is a clear alternative non-tolled route) there are no other tolled trunk routes in mainland </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Britain</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Wha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t tolled routes there a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">re, are all estuarial crossings;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:4.14pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The use of tolls would be inconsistent with the approach to other road upgrades. For example, in the 2012 Autumn Statement </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the Chancellor </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">announced £1.5 billion of new road schemes. None </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of these sche</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">mes will be tolled;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:4.14pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Tolls on the A14 would be discriminatory, adding costs to businesses in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ast of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that are not faced by businesses elsewhere. The A14 is the main trunk route connecting </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">East Anglia</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> with the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Midlands</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and North and is the only o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ption for many drivers. Unlike other regions with multiple access routes, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">East Anglia</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> relies heavily on two, the A14 to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the west and A12 to the south;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:4.14pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A toll would increase the cost of exports undermining economic recovery both in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">our</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> region, which is a ne</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t contributor to the Exchequer, and across UK plc. The Haven ports represent a major route to overseas markets for exporters based in the manufacturing heartlands of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Midlands</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and North. The majority of these e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">xports access ports via the A14;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:4.14pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A toll w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ou</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ld</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> distort competition between businesses located in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">East Anglia</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and competitors elsewhere which will have lower transport costs to get to market. Businesses in the region are likely to suffer economic loss as a result with potentially negative im</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">pacts for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> growth and employment;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:4.14pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Our members tell us that a toll would have a significant negative impact on inward investor confidence and on future inward investment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in the east of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> region</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. We have already been made aware of the plans of one major manufact</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">urer to re-locate out of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">County should a toll be imposed;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:4.14pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Many heavy goods haulage firms have a policy of not paying tolls. Tolls on the A14 will lead to traffic diverting onto less suitable alternative routes leading to an increase in congestio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n and a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ccidents on those routes; and</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:4.14pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The gross revenue raised will be insignificant in the context of the Highways Agency’s annual capital budget, representing just 2% of current budgets and less than 1% of future annual budgets. The net revenue will be even less</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> once the cost of toll-collection has been deducted. </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In this instance </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> formal consultation process by the Highways Agency </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">as badly conceiv</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ed and poorly implemented</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Suffolk Chamber </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of Commerce </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and many of our partners have responded to the consultation, and written to the Chancellor, asking that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">no decision </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11p