ore acts as an economic driver for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Suffolk</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">East Anglia</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and indeed UK plc.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Second, the Agency </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">has very recently</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> consult</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> on proposed improvements to the A14 between Huntingdon and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ambridge</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and on proposals to toll the new route. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Suffolk Chamber </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of Commerce </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">support</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> improvements </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">but at the same time has strong</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> concerns</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">at Government proposals to partly fund those improvements through tolling.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> public consultation exercise, led</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for Government by the Highways Agency and regarding the proposed improvements and tolling arrangements, was launched on 9 September </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">onclude</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> on 13 October 2013.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Chamber</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’s concerns </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">about the consultation process </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are based on a number of specific c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ircumstances which again illustrate the Agency’s disconnectedness from businesses and communities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. In particular:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:4.14pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The consultation period </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">was far </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">too brief to allow for meaningful engagement between the Highways Agency and affe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cted businesses and communiti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">es;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:4.14pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">All of the Highways Agency’s 8 public exhibitions during the current consultation period are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">took</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> place in Cambridgeshire; no exhibitions or formal consultations </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">took place in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Suffolk</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, Essex or</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Norfolk</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:4.14pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Highways Agency declined our invitation to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">attend a 24 September meeting of Suffolk Chamber’s Transport and Infrastructure Group (which acts as the local transport board to the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> New Anglia LEP Transport Body); and</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 10.06pt; padding-left:4.14pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">were</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> no formal consultation meetings between the Highways Agency and business representatives, outside Cambridgeshire, during the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">whole</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> process despite our requests.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">All of this suggest</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to us that Government </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">through the Agency had</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> already concluded that the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">improvements and proposed tolling are not a major issue</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for business</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Suffolk</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and other counties outside Cambridgeshire. This is not correct of course and seems to us to sit uncomfortably with Government’s wish to secure a wide base of financial contribu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tions towards the project, both up-front from local partners and in the longer term through tolling.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Whatever structural changes are made the Highways Agency will not become </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">“the world’s leading highway operator”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> unless it works collaboratively and positiv</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ely with businesses and local communities.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">October 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:C